    • Constructor Detail

      • Donkey

        public Donkey(java.io.File read)
       throws NoFileException,
              NoReadException,
              FileDirectoryException,
              InvalidFileException
        Create a Donkey class from a file.
        Creating a new Donkey object is useful for accessing methods being used and only having one file to execute, where using the main(String[]) method is useful for having multiple files to execute without a need for other methods.
        Parameters:
        read - The file to read from
        Throws:
        NoFileException - If the file does not exist
        NoReadException - If the file cannot be read
        FileDirectoryException - If the file is a directory
        InvalidFileException - If the file is not a .donkey file or is not a valid Donkey class file
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        main(String[])

    • Method Detail

      • main

        public static void main(java.lang.String... args)
                 throws NoFileException,
                        NoReadException,
                        FileDirectoryException,
                        InvalidFileException,
                        InvalidStatementException,
                        TypeDoesNotExistException,
                        IncompatibleVariableTypesException,
                        VariableAlreadyDeclaredException
        If given a null argument or 0 parameters, this will open a GUI for choosing a script. Given one or more file paths, this will run the code of those files.
        This method will instantly run each file's code and is useful for running several files of code, where creating a new Donkey object will allow you to access methods being used and is better for executing only one file's code.
        Parameters:
        args - The array of files to execute
        Throws:
        NoFileException - If the file does not exist
        NoReadException - If the file cannot be read
        FileDirectoryException - If the file is a directory
        InvalidFileException - If the file is not a .donkey file or is not a valid Donkey class file
        IncompatibleVariableTypesException - If a variable is assigned something that it cannot represent
        TypeDoesNotExistException - If a variable being assigned has not been declared
        VariableAlreadyDeclaredException - If a variable has already been declared
        InvalidStatementException - If a statement parses as invalid
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        Donkey(File)

      • runCode

        public void runCode()
             throws InvalidFileException,
                    TypeDoesNotExistException,
                    IncompatibleVariableTypesException,
                    VariableAlreadyDeclaredException
        Run the code. Automatically called in main(String[]), but you must manually run it when using the Donkey(File) constructor.
        Throws:
        InvalidFileException - If the file does not end with .donkey or is not a valid Donkey class file
        IncompatibleVariableTypesException - If a variable is assigned something that it cannot represent
        TypeDoesNotExistException - If a variable being assigned has not been declared
        VariableAlreadyDeclaredException - If a variable has already been declared
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        main(String[]), Donkey(File)
